        <recipe name="German sweet chocolate cake" serves="Cake">
            <notes> </notes>
            <ingredients>
                <ingredient type="group_1">
                    <item xml:id="choc" quantity="4" unit="ounce">Bakers German sweet chocolate<note resp="njk">1-4oz bar</note></item>
                    <!--ebb: So, @resp is sometimes used to indicate responsibility in TEI code. This is your
                    own markup, but we can adapt some of these things from the TEI. :-) -->
                    <item xml:id="bwater" quantity=".5" unit="cup">1/2 cup boiling water</item>
                    <item xml:id="butter" quantity="1" unit="cup">1 cup butter</item>
                    <item xml:id="sug" quantity="2" unit="cup">2 cups of sugar</item>
                    <item xml:id="egg-y" quantity="4" unit="egg-yolk">4 egg yolks</item>
                    <item xml:id="van" quantity="1" unit="tsp">1 tsp vanilla</item>
                </ingredient>
                <ingredient type="group_2"><!--In the schema, use a datatype for decimals: xsd:float -->
                    <item xml:id="cflour" quantity="2.5" unit="cup">2 1/2 cups sifted cake flour<note resp="njk">Swan or Softasilk</note>.</item>
                    <item xml:id="bsoda" quantity="1" unit="tsp">1 tsp baking soda</item>
                    <item xml:id="salt" quantity=".5" unit="tsp">1/2 tsp salt</item>
                    <item xml:id="bumilk" quantity="1" unit="cup">1 cup buttermilk</item>
                    <item xml:id="egg-w" quantity="4" unit="egg-white">4 egg whites<note resp="njk">stiffly beaten</note></item>
                </ingredient>
            </ingredients>
            <instructions>
                <!--ebb: Here's a coding challenge! How do you as the editor of this recipe add your own 
                knowledge of what's MISSING in these written steps? 
                Use the @resp attribute to point to your xml:id. 
                
                Do you want a photo (or two?) for each step? 
                
                What about teaching people how to separate an egg yolk from white?
                
                Do you want to give your commentary a little sass, style/tone? Think of your own new markup
                as written in your distinctive voice. You can make it funny, serious, etc. :-)
                -->
                <step action="melt"><!-- Continue marking the ingredients and use a @ref attribute to point back to the xml:id -->
                    <description>Melt <ing ref="choc">chocolate</ing> in boiling water, cool.</description>
                </step>
                <step action="cream"><!--ebb: What instruments are you using to cream the butter? -->
                    <description>Cream <ing ref="butter sug">butter &amp; sugar</ing> till fluffy.</description>
                </step>
                <step action="add"><!--ebb: Okay, how did you really do this?  -->
                    <description>Add egg yolks, 1 at a time, beating well. Blend in vanilla &amp;
                        chocolate.</description>
                </step>
                <step action="sift_and_add"><!--ebb: Wait, did we miss a step? When did we mix the buttermilk and chocolate? -->
                    <description>Sift flour with baking soda &amp; salt. Add alternately with
                        buttermilk/choco mixture. Beat till smooth.</description>
                </step>
                <step action="fold"><!-- ebb: Hey, what does she mean by "fold"? -->
                    <description>Fold in by hand beaten egg whites.</description>
                </step>
                <step action="bake"><!-- Add markup around temperatures in case someone is cooking England or Europe and using 
                Celsius instead of Fahrenheit. Do you want to mark timespans (that would have unit="minute" quantity="" too). -->
                    <description>Pour into 3 round cake pans lined with parchment paper. Bake at 350
                        for 30-35 min. Cool in pans 15-20 min. Flip and remove paper.</description>
                </step>
            </instructions>
        </recipe>

        <recipe name="Whipped Cream Frosting" serves="Frosting">
            <metadata>
                <source resp="njk akk">Gramma Mikula &amp; Mom K.</source>
                <date>2005</date><!-- ebb: Why 2005? -->
                <note resp="njk">On highest speed</note>
            </metadata>
            <ingredients>
                <ingredient type="beat_in_mixing_bowl"><!--ebb: I wonder if some things you described in the @type attributes should just be
                "unpacked" into your own editorial notes with @resp="eek"? -->
                    <item ref="egg-w" quantity="1" unit="egg-white">1 egg white</item>
                    <item xml:id="oleo" quantity=".5" unit="cup">1/2 cup oleo</item>
                    <item xml:id="crisco" quantity=".5" unit="cup">1/2 cup Crisco</item>
                </ingredient>
                <ingredient type="add">
                    <item ref="van" quantity="1" unit="tsp">1 tsp vanilla</item>
                    <item ref="sug" quantity="1" unit="cup">1 cup sugar</item>
                    <item xml:id="evmilk" quantity=".66" unit="cup">2/3 cup evaporated milk<note resp="njk">Small can = 2/3 cup</note>
                    </item>
                </ingredient>
            </ingredients>
            <instructions><!-- ebb: If you write up an equipment list, you could be referencing it here. -->
                <step action="beat">Beat ingredients in mixing bowl on highest speed.</step>
                <step action="add">Add the remaining ingredients.</step>
                <step action="mix">Mix until thick and fluffy.</step>
            </instructions>
        </recipe>
